  (2) None
  (3) Little
  (4) Any
ANSWER: (3)

ELABORATION (703 chars):
This question tests **negative inversion**, where starting a sentence with a **negative adverb** swaps the usual order of the **subject** and **helping verb**.

**(3) Little** is correct because it acts as a **negative adverb** meaning "almost not at all." Putting it at the start perfectly triggers the inverted order of the **helping verb** ("did") and **subject** ("the clown").

Why the others fail:
**(1) Much** is not a **negative adverb**, so it cannot trigger **negative inversion**.
**(2) None** is a **pronoun**, not an **adverb**, causing a mismatched sentence structure.
**(4) Any** is a **determiner** used with nouns in questions or negatives, not a starting word for an inverted sentence.

